article.headline: Portland wins another on the road
article.linkText: Blazers end Grizzlies' win streak at eight
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Memphis Grizzlies finally came out flat, and it ended the longest winning streak in franchise history. Zach Randolph had 21 points and nine rebounds Wednesday night as the Portland Trail Blazers relied on their physical play for an 88-76 victory over Memphis. Rasheed Wallace added 16 points and 10 rebounds for Portland, which has won the first two games on a three-game road trip. "We didn't let them go on any runs," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "I think that was the key. We didn't let them get back in the game." Portland's physical inside defense affected Memphis leading scorer Pau Gasol, who was held to 13 points on 4-of-15 shooting. Gasol consistently showed his frustration over the banging he took going to the basket. "That's the way they play with everybody," Gasol said. "They are a strong team, an athletic team. That's what they base their game on. It's a hard matchup for us. It would be hard for anybody in the league." The Grizzlies shot poorly, hitting only 32 percent -- a season low. Portland took a 78-66 lead on a 3-pointer by Derek Anderson with 5:27 left, and the Trail Blazers never let their edge get below double digits the rest of the way. Anderson and reserve Ruben Patterson finished with 12 points. Bonzi Wells, acquired from Portland earlier this season, led the Grizzlies with 20 points. A lot of those came from Wells driving to the basket against the banging Trail Blazers, a style with which he is familiar. "That was our whole thing," Wells said reflecting on his time in Portland. "To just get rough with guys. We wanted to keep our bodies on them. "The might have out-physicaled us." The Trail Blazers led by as many as nine in the first half, but a 13-4 run by Memphis tied the game at 29. Portland closed the half with an 11-5 to take a 40-34 lead. Randolph hit all but one of his seven shots from the field. He also grabbed seven rebounds in the half. "We had so many opportunities in the first half," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said, " but we either missed shots or we turned it over. We had some key people that struggled big time." Patterson's steal from Wells and subsequent dunk with a second left gave the Trail Blazers a 64-60 lead entering the fourth. Portland extended the lead to 80-66 midway through the period thanks to 11 straight points. Wells acknowledged that while streaks will always end, he wished another team had stopped the Grizzlies' run. "I wish we all could have played well," Wells said. "You just hate to lose, especially to Portland, for me personally."

Game notes
The league announced Wednesday that the Grizzlies-Utah Jazz game postponed Jan. 7 because of travel problems has been rescheduled for April 5. The game at Utah creates a road back-to-back for the Grizzlies, who play the day before in Minnesota. ...The Grizzlies' 14 first-quarter points matched their season low for the opening stanza. Memphis had more rebounds (15) than points in the quarter. ... Mike Miller left the game in the second half with back spasms. His status is day-to-day. ... Randolph has averaged 25 points and 14 rebounds in the last four games against Memphis. ... The loss also snapped Memphis' seven-game home winning streak. ... Wesley Person hit one of two from 3-point range. He has hit 17 of his last 27 shots from outside the arc. ...Randolph has scored in double figures in all but one game this season -- a 7-point performance Jan. 9 at Chicago.
